    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-08-27T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-08-27T06:00:00-05:00" n="128"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d128">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/135: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-08-27T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 27, 1929—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received August 27—10:12
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>245. …</p>
                <p>On arrival at the office this morning I found following letter from the Prime
                    Minister.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“26th August, 1929.</p>
                    <p>My dear General Dawes: On further examination of the despatch of the 23rd
                            instant,<note n="44" xml:id="d128fn44">See telegram No. 242, August 24,
                            from the Ambassador in Great Britain, <ref target="#pg_196">p.
                            196</ref>.</note> I see that I did not make it as clear as I ought to
                        have done in paragraph 17 that the figures I quoted as having been used by
                        Mr. Gibson were not official figures and not binding in any way on the
                        American Government. Since my return I have been informed that they were
                        only used in purely personal conversation as something which might happen
                        when we got into closer grips in making an agreement.</p>
                    <p>I am, yours very sincerely, J. Ramsay MacDonald.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>The Foreign Office asks that for purposes of reference the Prime Minister’s
                    undated letter “in my 242, August 24, 2 p.m., be dated August 23rd.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
